(lldb) why What is the root cause of this crash? Walk through the program state, identify the defect, and propose a fix in code. Cover both a minimal local fix and a more thorough root-cause fix if they differ.
                                                                                
    Root‑cause analysis                                                         
                                                                                
     1 Program state at the moment of the crash                                 
        • int *n = new int(100); allocates a single int on the heap and stores  
          its address in n.                                                     
        • n--; performs pointer arithmetic, moving the raw pointer backward by  
          one int size (typically 4 bytes). The resulting address now points    
          outside the region that was allocated.                                
        • delete n; attempts to free the memory at that out‑of‑bounds address.  
          The runtime detects that the memory was not allocated with new (or    
          was not the original allocation) and raises the “Deallocation of      
          non‑allocated memory” error.                                          
        • After the illegal delete, the program continues and executes          
          doSomething(n); (which may read or write through the now‑invalid      
          pointer) and then std::cout << "n = " << *n << std::endl;. This is a  
          use‑after‑free situation, which reinforces the crash and would        
          produce undefined behaviour even if the first delete succeeded.       
     2 Why this triggers the observed error                                     
       The error message “Deallocation of non‑allocated memory” is emitted by   
       the C++ runtime when delete is called on a pointer that does not refer   
       to a block allocated with new[] or new. Because n-- changed the pointer  
       value, the subsequent delete no longer matches any allocation, causing   
       the runtime to abort with the reported diagnosis.                        
     3 Minimal local fix                                                        
       The immediate fix is to remove the offending pointer adjustment and the  
       subsequent use of the now‑invalid pointer:                               
                                                                                
        int *n = new int(100);                                                  
        // delete n--;   // <-- remove this line                                
        delete n;       // delete the memory that was actually allocated        
        char *ch = new char[16];                                                
        delete [] ch;                                                           
        doSomething(n); // now safe – n still points to the allocated int       
        std::cout << "n = " << *n << std::endl;                                 
                                                                                
       If the intent was to work with an array of ints, allocate an array       
       instead:                                                                 
                                                                                
        int *n = new int[1];          // allocate one element                   
        // no decrement!                                                        
        delete n;                     // free the allocated element             
                                                                                
       Or, even better, use a scalar int without a raw pointer:                 
                                                                                
        int n = 100;                                                            
        doSomething(&n);   // pass address if the function really needs a       
        pointer                                                                 
                                                                                
     4 More thorough root‑cause fix                                             
       The underlying design flaw is the manual, raw pointer management         
       combined with pointer arithmetic that is not justified by the intended   
       semantics. A robust solution would eliminate raw pointers altogether or  
       at least encapsulate them in an RAII type:                               
                                                                                
        #include <memory>                                                       
        #include <iostream>                                                     
                                                                                
        void doSomething(int *ptr) {                                            
            *ptr = 0;                                                           
        }                                                                       
                                                                                
        int main() {                                                            
            // Use a smart pointer that automatically manages lifetime          
            std::unique_ptr<int> n = std::make_unique<int>(100);                
                                                                                
            // No pointer arithmetic; just pass the raw pointer if needed       
            doSomething(n.get());                                               
                                                                                
            // No use‑after‑free possible – n goes out of scope automatically   
            std::cout << "n = " << *n << std::endl;                             
                                                                                
            // Allocate and free the char buffer safely                         
            std::unique_ptr<char[]> ch = std::make_unique<char[]>(16);          
            // ... use ch ...                                                   
        }                                                                       
                                                                                
       Benefits of this approach                                                
        • No manual new/delete pair to mismanage.                               
        • The pointer is guaranteed to be valid for the whole lifetime of the   
          object.                                                               
        • delete is performed automatically when the unique_ptr goes out of     
          scope, eliminating leftover delete calls that could become dangling.  
        • If more complex buffer handling is required, std::vector<int> or      
          std::array<int, N> can replace the manual allocation.                 
     5 Why the deeper fix matters                                               
       Even if you kept the raw pointer for educational purposes, you would     
       still need to enforce strict invariants:                                 
        • No pointer arithmetic that moves the pointer away from the original   
          allocation unless you also store the original base address and later  
          restore it.                                                           
        • Never delete a pointer that has been altered unless you have a        
          corresponding original pointer to delete.                             
        • Never access a pointer after it has been deleted.                     
       By adopting smart pointers and avoiding raw pointer manipulation, the    
       code becomes self‑documenting and the runtime can enforce lifetimes      
       automatically, preventing both the “deallocation of non‑allocated        
       memory” and the subsequent use‑after‑free errors.                        
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
    Fix: Remove the n--; line and the subsequent delete n; (or replace the raw  
    allocation with a proper container/smart pointer). If you truly need to     
    manipulate the pointer value, store the original address separately and     
    restore it before deletion.                                                 
                                                                                
    Additional suggestions (if you prefer incremental debugging):               
                                                                                
     1 Insert a check before the delete: assert(n >= original_allocation_start  
       && n < original_allocation_end); to catch invalid deletes early.         
     2 Replace new/delete with std::unique_ptr/std::shared_ptr throughout the   
       project to make memory management explicit and exception‑safe.           
     3 Run the program under AddressSanitizer (-fsanitize=address) to get a     
       clear diagnostic of the out‑of‑bounds delete and any subsequent          
       use‑after‑free.                                                          
                                                                                
    These steps will eliminate the immediate crash and prevent related          
    memory‑safety bugs in the future.                                           
                                                                                
